The Borough of Kettering was a [non-metropolitan district](/Non-metropolitan_district) and [borough](/Borough_status_in_the_United_Kingdom) that existed within [England](/England) from 1974 until 2021. It was situated in the county of [Northamptonshire](/Northamptonshire), a part of the [East Midlands](/East_Midlands) region. The borough took its name from its primary urban centre, [Kettering](/Kettering), which also served as the administrative headquarters for the council. Its geographical boundaries abutted several other administrative divisions. To the west, it bordered the [Harborough](/Harborough_District) district, which fell under the jurisdiction of Leicestershire, a neighbouring county. Within Northamptonshire, it shared frontiers with the [borough of Corby](/Corby_(borough)) to the north, the district of [East Northamptonshire](/East_Northamptonshire) to the east, the district of [Daventry](/Daventry_District) to the southwest, and the [borough of Wellingborough](/Borough_of_Wellingborough) to the south.

### Abolition and Replacement

The administrative landscape of Northamptonshire underwent a significant transformation culminating in the abolition of the Borough of Kettering. This change was precipitated by a series of events that led to the suspension of the county council in March 2018, a consequence of its becoming insolvent. The root causes were attributed to what was described as financial and cultural mismanagement by its cabinet and officers. In response to this crisis, the then Secretary of State for Local Government, [Sajid Javid](/Sajid_Javid), initiated an inquiry, dispatching [commissioner](/Commissioner) Max Caller to investigate the council's operations.

Caller's subsequent recommendations were stark: he advised the abolition of both the county council and all existing district and borough councils within Northamptonshire. His proposal advocated for the establishment of two new [unitary authorities](/Unitary_authorities_of_England), each with a broader remit, to govern the county. One of these new entities was designated to oversee the western part of the county, while the other would manage the northern territories.

These proposals received approval in April 2019. The restructuring meant that the districts of [Daventry](/Daventry_District), [Northampton](/Northampton), and [South Northamptonshire](/South_Northamptonshire) were consolidated to form a new unitary authority known as [West Northamptonshire](/West_Northamptonshire). Concurrently, the remaining districts – [Corby](/Corby_(borough)), [East Northamptonshire](/East_Northamptonshire), Kettering, and [Wellingborough](/Borough_of_Wellingborough) – were merged to create the second unitary authority, christened [North Northamptonshire](/North_Northamptonshire). These new administrative bodies officially commenced their operations on 1 April 2021. The initial elections for these new authorities were scheduled for 7 May 2020, but were subsequently postponed due to the global impact of the [COVID-19 pandemic](/COVID-19_pandemic).

### Settlements and Parishes

Beyond the principal town of Kettering, the administrative area encompassed a number of smaller settlements and civil parishes. These included:

*   [Ashley](/Ashley,_Northamptonshire)
*   [Barton Seagrave](/Barton_Seagrave), [Brampton Ash](/Brampton_Ash), [Braybrooke](/Braybrooke), [Broughton](/Broughton,_Northamptonshire), [Burton Latimer](/Burton_Latimer)
*   [Cranford](/Cranford,_Northamptonshire), [Cransley](/Cransley)
*   [Desborough](/Desborough), [Dingley](/Dingley,_Northamptonshire)
*   [Geddington](/Geddington), [Grafton Underwood](/Grafton_Underwood)
*   [Harrington](/Harrington,_Northamptonshire)
*   [Loddington](/Loddington,_Northamptonshire)
*   [Mawsley](/Mawsley) Village
*   [Newton and Little Oakley](/Newton_and_Little_Oakley)
*   [Orton](/Orton,_Northamptonshire)
*   [Pytchley](/Pytchley)
*   [Rothwell](/Rothwell,_Northamptonshire), [Rushton](/Rushton,_Northamptonshire)
*   [Stoke Albany](/Stoke_Albany), [Sutton Bassett](/Sutton_Bassett)
*   [Thorpe Malsor](/Thorpe_Malsor)
*   [Warkton](/Warkton), [Weekley](/Weekley), [Weston by Welland](/Weston_by_Welland), [Wilbarston](/Wilbarston)

